TY  - JOUR
AU  - Washington, Ebonya
T1  - How Black Candidates Affect Voter Turnout*
PY  - 2006
Y1  - 2006/08/01
DO  - 10.1162/qjec.121.3.973
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 121
IS  - 3
SP  - 973
EP  - 998
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Both Black and White voter turnout increases 2–3 percentage points with each Black Democrat on the ballot. Given the groups' representations in the population, the White response is numerically greater. Whites of both parties are less likely to vote for their parties' candidate when s/he is Black. The turnout findings are not explained away by voter, election, or politician characteristics. However, the fact that there is no turnout response to Black Republicans suggests that a perception of Blacks' ideology may be a factor.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/qjec.121.3.973
ER  - 



