TY  - JOUR
AU  - Gentzkow, Matthew
T1  - Television and Voter Turnout*
PY  - 2006
Y1  - 2006/08/01
DO  - 10.1162/qjec.121.3.931
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 121
IS  - 3
SP  - 931
EP  - 972
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - I use variation across markets in the timing of television's introduction to identify its impact on voter turnout. The estimated effect is significantly negative, accounting for between a quarter and a half of the total decline in turnout since the 1950s. I argue that substitution away from other media with more political coverage provides a plausible mechanism linking television to voting. As evidence for this, I show that the entry of television in a market coincided with sharp drops in consumption of newspapers and radio, and in political knowledge as measured by election surveys. I also show that both the information and turnout effects were largest in off-year congressional elections, which receive extensive coverage in newspapers but little or no coverage on television.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/qjec.121.3.931
ER  - 



